						<p>The other fact that remains is that any other creature but Rochester's man resolves this problem 100% of the time : "I have an army ; and I am to take that city. Therefore we march at dawn."</p>
<p>The fundamental limit here exposed, by Lamport, or Shannon, or otherwise by Turing, or Godel, or others, is simply that you can not know the future, and this is never going to change. No matter which way you try, you'll find a rock in the way ; and whichever way you choose to name that rock, that exercise in nymics does not institute some sort of ownership or control over the rock in your favour, nor does it take you any closer to "solving" anything - the rock stays. Plan accordingly.</p>
<p>And therefore, march at dawn.</p>
